The Wnt/β-catenin pathway is a central regulator of colorectal cancer (CRC) stemness and tumor progression. In canonical Wnt signaling, Wnt ligands (e.g., WNT3A) bind to Frizzled (FZD) receptors and LRP5/6 co-receptors, inhibiting the β-catenin destruction complex (comprising APC, AXIN, GSK-3β, and CK1α). Stabilized β-catenin translocates to the nucleus, where it partners with TCF/LEF transcription factors to activate genes (e.g., *MYC*, *CCND1*, *LGR5*) that drive self-renewal, proliferation, and chemoresistance in CRC stem cells (CR-CSCs). Non-canonical Wnt pathways (e.g., Wnt/PCP) further support metastasis via Rho GTPase and JNK signaling. Clinically, ~90% of sporadic CRCs harbor APC mutations, while ~20% have CTNNB1 (β-catenin) mutations, underscoring its therapeutic relevance. Targeting strategies include:
1) **Small-molecule inhibitors**: Porcupine inhibitors (e.g., LGK974) block Wnt ligand secretion, with trials (NCT01351103) showing limited efficacy due to compensatory pathways;
2) **Biologics**: Anti-FZD antibodies (e.g., OMP-18R5) and decoy receptors (e.g., ipafricept) neutralize Wnt ligands, but toxicities (e.g., bone loss) remain a concern;
3) **Epigenetic modulators**: BET inhibitors (e.g., JQ1) suppress β-catenin-driven transcription;
4) **ASOs**: Targeting *LGR5* or *MYC* in CR-CSCs;
5) **Immunotherapy**: Combining Wnt inhibitors with checkpoint blockers (e.g., anti-PD-1) to overcome immune evasion. Emerging research focuses on identifying Wnt-high CR-CSC subsets via single-cell RNA-seq and developing nanoparticles for targeted delivery. Despite progress, Wnt pathway redundancy and toxicity limit monotherapy success, necessitating combination regimens.

